@node manualserver "MARInA, ©'1998 by Thomas Neidhardt: ManualServer..."
@prev main

  @{" < " link main} @{b}MARInA Wizards@{ub}

        ©'98 Thomas Neidhardt, 91058 Erlangen, GERMANY
____________________________________________________________________



    @{b}Fully featured Online-Help Management System@{ub}

    for system-wide distributed Application-Documents 
    based on various Document-Types such as .dvi, .hguide, .guide, 
    .doc, .dok, ... (Destination-Directories and FileTypes/Viewers 
    are user customizable). 

    Just work out a plan and then enhance the Config File

    @{"   " link MARInA_rexx:Manual.config/main} MARInA_rexx:manual.config

    once with your desired Document-Directories, FileTypes and viewers
    and place the MARInA Manual Server as a ToolManager-Dock-Icon:

    @{" + " SYSTEM "run <>NIL: ${RefTable/ManualServer}"} Call by Shell: @{i}${RefTable/ManualServer}@{ui}


    As far as your Manual-Server Configuration is configured correctly:
    (I will answer questions to that Configuration File
    MARInA_rexx:Manual.config by EMail)

        * if you need help for a program, you may in future only drag
          the program's icon onto the MARInA ManualServer Dock. It will
          then presentate the Documentation if available in one of the
          supplied directories.

        * furthermore, if you have configured it to use multiple
          languages, it will presentate the document in your preferred
          Language, as far as available.

        * Clicking the Dock lets you specify the keyword (e.g.  screentab)
          and then will present the Documents for ScreenTab, while
          scanning the given Destination-Directories and Document-Types
          just as when ...

          typing

          > man screentab    in your shell will serve the same result

          > man mydir/ScreenTab.guide  will start the Installation-Server
                                       for documents.

          thus even Shell-enthousiasts get what they want.

        * Dropping a Document File (.doc, .dok, .guide, ... ) onto the
          Dock will initiate an automatic driven dialog which is called
          the Documents-Manager. It will shovle or tie the passed
          documents to your predefined Destinations. It is advisable
          to rename documents with names like "ScreenTab.deutsch.guide"
          that contain a Language delimiter, so that they represent only
          the related Tool. Should mean "ScreenTab.guide" will be the
          correct name for the Installation-Server.

    Multiple Language Documentation is customizable and supported.

    In this scope, it is advisable, to have at least for each Partition
    a directory

        Help/deutsch ...
        Help/english ...
        Help/français ...
        ...

        (e.g.) so just take your two or three major Languages. Thus
        in future, newer supplied docs will be stored there.

    I use to have several locations on my partitions where I let the
    system store the Documents:

        Sound:      (logic assign to a directory containing audio
                    related tools and binaries)
        Gfx:        (logic assign to a directory containing graphics
                    and video tools or binaries)
        Tech:       (Partition containing technical stuff for CAD,
                    electronic design ...)
        Net:        (logic assign to a directory containing every
                    network related tools and applications such as
                    Miami, YAM, IBrowse, ... and their StartScripts
                    in ARexx)
        ...

    (kind of 'object oriented' Directories) ... further, when installing
    a new package from Aminet, I always let the ManualServer install three
    Language's (deutsch, english, français, my preferred Languages in
    a row of priority) documents if available with the archive. Thus,
    switching the system by Locale-Prefs, the ManualServer will also
    supply documents of the newly selected Language if available, if not,
    it will supply the next available document in the priority-list.

    This @{b}switching of Languages@{ub} is one of the most unique features and
    as well one of the most misjudged abilities of the AMIGA!

    The System-Language may be switched by using the System-Tool
    "SYS:Prefs/Locale". To do that, first clear the actually viewn
    language list, pressing the right top button in the window.
    Then choose the preferred Language(s) out of the list of available
    languages in the order of your priority. Press "Use" or "Save" now,
    and you're ready to work using that language.

    Every program, that supports that language (means, that it has been
    installed with it's various catalogs or Help-files correctly),
    will upon now run in italiano, e.g.

    On international multimedia Info-Systems, respectively, but also
    for international developer's conferences, this is an eye-catching
    and still today revolutionary concept.

____________________________________________________________________
@endnode


@node backupmanager "MARInA, ©'1998 by Thomas Neidhardt: Backups..."
@prev main

  @{" < " link main} @{b}MARInA Wizards@{ub}

        ©'98 Thomas Neidhardt, 91058 Erlangen, GERMANY
____________________________________________________________________


   @{b}Fully customizable and talking(!) AmigaDOS-based
   @{" + " SYSTEM "run <>NIL: ${RefTable/BackupManager}"} BackupManager@{ub}: @{i}${RefTable/BackupManager}@{ui}

        (included with the MARInA_Plus package)

        for incremental or complete Backups of Partitions or even
        parts (files, directories) of them. Just predefine your
        Config-Files once, then choose the desired Config by
        FileRequester and the Backup (e.g. to a Syquest 270MB
        Cartridge) will be completed. Each Backup-Partition will
        be supplied with a customizable Icon and IconPosition.

        All functions GUI-driven.
        I don't use any other BackupTools anymore since I've
        coded the MARInA Backup-Manager. It's most intuitive and
        easiest in use. Perhaps it is not as fast as others but
        you've got a multitasking Amiga, just do other nice things
        while the Backup is working!

        And, other BackupTools provide
        an own FileSystem, thus the data could easily get totally lost
        if there appears an error on the Backup Medium. As opposed
        to this kind of Backup: The Data are simply copied to a
        preformatted AmigaDOS-Partition (Syquest, e.g.).

        The advantages are clear:

            * Better protection against Data-Loss
            * You may access all data directly, whith means of daily
              work, such as the MARInA FileManager, other FileManagers,
              Workbench, DirOpus ...
            * The Backup (e.g., one of the SYS: Partition) may be used
              as a 100% Emergency-Boot-System, if your System-Harddisk
              should be striking.

        The MARInA Backup-Manager will rimind you by the
        decent female voice when it has completed it's work. MARInA!
        (as far as you have configured MARInA to talk).

____________________________________________________________________
@endnode
